This problem can easily be solved with **pointer to the last sum and Greedy approach.**
It is very similar to this problem: https://leetcode.com/problems/contiguous-array/

The point is - any number of items , whose sum is 0 , will have the same sum with previous items and these items. 
Example explains everything:
[3 ,5, 7, -3,-2,-2, 6]

We can deduct that 7,-3,-2,-2 gives us 0.  So the sum of all previous numbers should be equal to all previous + these numbers which give us 0.
Let's calculate sum of all elements
arr  = [3, 5,  7,  -3, -2, -2,  6]
cnt = [3, **8**,15, 12,10,  **8**, 14]
As we can see , we have 2 **8** sums. So we're sure that items between 8's are giving 0. 

But what if we find another 8 later? The same thing  - the sum between the first 8 and the last will be equal to 0, so all of these items can be removed. 

arr  = [3, 5,  7,  -3, -2, -2,  6,  -6]
cnt = [3, **8**,15, 12,10,  **8**, 14, **8**]
All of these items from first till last together will give the sum of 0.

As the result, we need to know where the last 8 (or any other number) is located. 
To keep track of the latest item with any sum , we'll use ```HashMap```.
By going through an array, the latest sum will just override previous item. 
```
    HashMap<Integer, ListNode> map = new HashMap(); 
	int sum = 0;

	for(ListNode pointer = head; pointer != null;  pointer = pointer.next){
		sum+= pointer.val;
		map.put(sum, pointer);
	}
```

!! If we see 0 as the sum, we need to delete all items between this last 0 , and first one. The point is that the place where we saw 0 first time was before any sum operations, which means that we have to delete all items before this item. 
In our case - just set ```head``` to item with 0 sum. 

After that, we iterate through the same nodes again, but this time we'll be looking for the same sums in the hashmap, and rellocating our pointer there. 
If we find 0 sum, we'll rellocate the head to this item as well ( because everything before will give us 0)

**Try to play with this solution on paper and try to create your own algorithm similar to this - this is how you learn things! Just reading and copy-pasting will not be enough!**

Here's the full solution:
```
class Solution {
    public ListNode removeZeroSumSublists(ListNode head) {
        HashMap<Integer, ListNode> map = new HashMap();

        int sum = 0;
        for(ListNode pointer = head; pointer != null;  pointer = pointer.next){
            sum+= pointer.val;
            map.put(sum, pointer);
        }

        sum = 0;
        for(ListNode pointer = head; pointer != null;  pointer = pointer.next){
            sum+= pointer.val;
            ListNode node = map.get(sum);
            if(sum == 0) head = node.next;
            if(node != pointer) pointer.next = node.next ;
        }
        return head;
    }
}
```

