Logic:
Example:
[3 ,5, 7, -3,-2,-2, 6]

We can observe that sum of **7,-3,-2,-2** gives us 0.

Let's calculate sum of all elements
arr = [3, 5, 7, -3, -2, -2, 6]
cnt = [3, **8**,15, 12,10, **8**, 14]
As we can see , we have 2 times **8** sums. ***So we're sure that items between 8's are summing to 0.***

But what if we find another 8 later? The sum between the **first 8 and the last 8** will be equal to 0, so all of the items in between can be removed.

arr = [3, 5, 7, -3, -2, -2, 6, -6]
cnt = [3, **8**,15, 12,10, 8, 14, **8**]
Sum of the items from **first 8 till last 8** will equal 0.

Hence, **we need to know where the last 8 (or any other number)** is located.

If we see 0 as the sum, we need to delete all items first 0 and last 0.

Then, we iterate through the same nodes again, but this time we'll be looking for the same sum in the hashmap, and rellocating our pointer there.
If we find sum=0, we'll rellocate the head to this item as well ( because everything before will give us 0)

Check the below code, you will understand better!

```
class Solution {
    public ListNode removeZeroSumSublists(ListNode head) {


        Map<Integer,ListNode> map= new HashMap<>();

        ListNode fake= new ListNode(0);
        fake.next=head;

        int sum=0;

        for(ListNode cur=fake; cur!=null; cur=cur.next)
        {
            sum= sum+cur.val;
            map.put(sum,cur);
        }

        sum=0;

        for(ListNode cur=fake; cur!=null; cur=cur.next)
        {
            sum= sum+cur.val;
            cur.next= map.get(sum).next;
        }

        return fake.next;

    }
}
```

