solutions.content:
After working on this problem for quite some time, I figured out the following:
1) The vowel 'a' always has 5 children
2) The vowel 'e' always has 4 children
3) The vowel 'i' always has 3 children
4) and so on ...


------
So if i was to draw a tree it would look like this:

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/e7ddc038-d84c-4687-87af-2191b1bde0cd_1607019474.8288138.png)

If you notice each layer of the tree, and analyse it we get the following arrays:

Depth = 1 : [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
Depth = 2 : [15, 10, 6, 3, 1]
Depth = 3 : [35, 20, 10, 4, 1]
and so on..

**At each depth the array is the presum array of the one before to it.**

#### Presum function : 
```
void presum(vector<int>& A)
{
	for(int i=1;i<5;++i)
		A[i] += A[i-1];
}
```

------

I will start with ``[1, 1, 1, 1, 1]``, say for layer 1.

1) We run a loop from **1 to n-1**, to calculate the presum each time. 
2) Then simply find the sum of the array elements.

#### Main function :

```
int countVowelStrings(int n)
{
	vector<int> A(5, 1);
	for(int i=1;i<n;++i)
		presum(A);

	int sum = 0;
	for(int i=0;i<5;++i)
		sum += A[i];

	return sum;
}
```

------
### Full Code:
```
class Solution {
public:
    void presum(vector<int>& A)
    {
        for(int i=1;i<5;++i)
            A[i] += A[i-1];
    }

    int countVowelStrings(int n)
    {
        vector<int> A(5, 1);
        for(int i=1;i<n;++i)
            presum(A);

        int sum = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<5;++i)
            sum += A[i];

        return sum;
    }
};
```

*I realize that the code could be optimised a lot, but the point of this is to give a solution that makes sense to most people.*

