Since the order of alphabets has to lexicographic, the relative positions of all 5 vowels is fixed. The only thing we need to find is the count of occurence of each vowel. Let us say the counts are x1,x2...,x5
Therefore, x1+x2+x3+x4+x5 = n (All xi's>=0)
The number of ways for the above equation is (4+n)C(n) (I've added the general formula below), which on simplifying becomes 
((n+1)*(n+2)*(n+3)*(n+4))/4!
```
 int countVowelStrings(int n) {
        return ((n+1)*((n+2)*((n+3)*(n+4))/2)/3)/4;
  }
  ```
  The general formula when we have r non-negative integers which add upto an integer n is: (n+r-1)C(r-1)

