**Method 1:** Brute force
**T/S:** O(n^4)/O(n) (not certain about time, best guess)
```
public int countVowelStrings(int n) {
	return countVowelStrings(n, 0);
}

private int countVowelStrings(int n, int v) {
	if (n == 0)
		return 1;
	var count = 0;
	for (var i = v; i < 5; i++)
		count += countVowelStrings(n - 1, i);
	return count;
}
```

**Method 2:** Inject Memoization in method 1
**T/S:** O(n)/O(n)
```
public int countVowelStrings(int n) {
	return countVowelStrings(n, 0, new char[]{'a', 'e', 'i', 'o', 'u'}, new HashMap<>());
}

private int countVowelStrings(int n, int v, char[] chars, Map<String, Integer> map) {
	if (n == 0)
		return 1;
	var key = chars[v] + "," + n;
	if (map.containsKey(key))
		return map.get(key);
	var count = 0;
	for (var i = v; i < 5; i++)
		count += countVowelStrings(n - 1, i, chars, map);
	map.put(key, count);
	return count;
}
```

**Method 3:** Tabulation. Time beats 100%
**T/S:** O(n)/O(n)
```
public int countVowelStrings(int n) {
	var count = new int[n + 1][5];
	for (var i = 0; i < n + 1; i++)
		count[i][0] = 1;
	Arrays.fill(count[0], 1);
	for (var i = 1; i < n + 1; i++)
		for (var j = 1; j < 5; j++)
			count[i][j] = count[i - 1][j] + count[i][j - 1];
	return count[n][4];
}
```

