solutions.content:
The main intuition behind this solution is, if we know number of valid permutations of sorted strings of length n-1 starting with a, e, i, o, u, say a(n-1), e(n-1), i(n-1), o(n-1), u(n-1).
In order to get sorted n length strings we can add a, e, i, o, u before n-1 length strings. Now we can not add u before strings starting with a/e/i/o. We can only add u before string starting with u.
so,          u(n) = u(n-1)              [u(n) will always be 1 as if a string starts with u, to keep it sorted we can only add u to it.)
simillarly o(n) = o(n-1) + u(n-1)  = o(n-1) + u(n)   add o before strings starting with o/u
i(n) = i(n-1) + o(n-1) + u(n-1) = i(n-1) + o(n)     add i before strings starting with i/o/u
e(n) = e(n-1) + i(n-1) + o(n-1) + u(n-1) = e(n-1) + i(n)    add e before strings starting with e/i/o/u
a(n) = a(n-1)  +  e(n-1) + i(n-1) + o(n-1) + u(n-1) = a(n-1) + e(n)

And finally Total T(n) = a(n) + e(n) + i(n) + o(n) + u(n)
base case is a(1) = 1, e(1) =1, i(1) =1, o(1) =1 and u(!) = 1.

```
class Solution {
    public int countVowelStrings(int n) {
        int[][] dp = new int[n][5];
        Arrays.fill(dp[0],1);
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=4;j>=0;j--){
                dp[i][j] = j==4?1:dp[i-1][j] + dp[i][j+1];
            }
        }
        int res = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<5;i++){
            res+=dp[n-1][i];
        }
        return res;
    }
}
```

