The trick is realizing that if there are an even number of negative numbers, all negatives can be eliminated and the answer is the sum of the absolute values of all elements. If there are an odd number of negative numbers, all negatives can be eliminated except for one. This one negative can be any number in the matrix, so we pick the smallest.

The code below loops through the matrix once keeping track of the sum of the absolute value of each element, the closest to zero element (minimum element after taking absolute value), and the number of negative numbers.

After the loop if there are an even number of negative numbers, we simply return the sum. If there are an odd number, we subtract two times the minimum element from the sum and return it.

```
long long maxMatrixSum(int** matrix, int matrixSize, int* matrixColSize){
    long long matrixSum = 0;
    int numNegative = 0, minimum = INT_MAX;

    for (int i = 0; i < matrixSize; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < matrixSize; j++) {
            if (matrix[i][j] < 0) numNegative++;
            if (abs(matrix[i][j]) < minimum) minimum = abs(matrix[i][j]);
            matrixSum += abs(matrix[i][j]);
        }
    }

    if (numNegative % 2 == 0) return matrixSum;
    return matrixSum - (2 * minimum);
}
```

