You can see that in each row there are two outputs. 
If there are odd number of minus numbers there has to be one number that after the multiply will still be a minus number. 
If there are even number of minus numbers all the number can become positive. 
beacuse adjacent elemntes are also defined by column you can move minus numbers from one row to another so all we have to do is to count the number of all minus numbers in the matrix. 
If they are even we can just return the abs sum of the matrix, and if they are odd we can play with the operations to remain with the closest number to zero as our only minus number .
I hope it's help 

```
class Solution {
    public long maxMatrixSum(int[][] matrix) {
        long sum = 0;
        int min = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        int minusCounter = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < matrix.length; i++ ) {
            for (int j = 0; j < matrix.length; j++) {
                if (matrix[i][j] < 0) {
                    minusCounter++;
                    sum +=(long) -matrix[i][j];
                    min = Math.min(min, -matrix[i][j]);
                } else {
                    sum +=(long) matrix[i][j];
                    min = Math.min(min, matrix[i][j]);
                }
            }
        }
        return minusCounter % 2 == 0 ? sum : sum - (long) 2*min;
    }
}
