solutions.content:
Would the task be easier with the following description?
_You are given an n x n integer matrix. You can do the following operation any number of times: take any two negative numbers and convert them to positive_ 

The problem states: 
_Choose any two adjacent elements of matrix and multiply each of them by -1_
As if you can eliminate minuses of two adjacent cells only.
But actually you can eliminate any two minuses on the field, because all intermediate cells keep their signs when you build a path through them. 
Let's construct a path from "two adjacent cells" building blocks. It can turn but for the simplicity we draw a horizontal path. Notice, that all intermediate cells in the path will be reverted twice => will keep their signs. 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/70b573bf-e8d6-45b8-9439-07fec21e2d17_1645198456.8017545.png)

Now we know that any two negative numbers can be changed to positive numbers. We are good if there is an even amount of negative numbers. If there is an odd amount, we can't eliminate 1 negative number.  

```
class Solution {
    public long maxMatrixSum(int[][] matrix) {
        int N = matrix.length;
        int min = Math.abs(matrix[0][0]);
        long sum = 0;
        int minuses = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < N; j++) {
                int abs = Math.abs(matrix[i][j]);
                sum += abs;
                min = Math.min(min, abs);
                if (matrix[i][j] < 0) {
                    minuses++;
                }
            }
        }
        if (minuses % 2 == 1) {
            sum -= (2 * min);
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

